=== STEP: ask-risks ===
--- cmd: bny brane ask what are the biggest technical and product risks? ---
asking brane...
# Biggest Technical and Product Risks

## Technical Risks

### 1. Launch-Day Meltdown
The API's value proposition peaks at exactly the moment it's most likely to fail. Waitlists experience 100x traffic spikes during viral moments, and position calculation via rank queries (`COUNT(*) WHERE score > ?`) becomes a table scan bottleneck at scale. If the API goes down during a founder's Product Hunt launch, there's no recovery — that founder is gone forever. The infrastructure must handle burst concurrency from day one, not "eventually."

### 2. Position Calculation Doesn't Scale Naively
Derived position (rank query per request) is clean architecturally but deadly under load. Every signup changes every other user's position, and every position check is a concurrent read against a moving target. The choice between materialized positions (write amplification) and rank queries (read amplification) is a lose-lose that needs careful engineering — approximate/cached positions with eventual consistency is likely the only viable path, but that undermines the "transparent, real-time position" product promise.

### 3. Referral Code Write Contention
A single viral referrer (someone whose tweet blows up) creates a hot row. Every signup using their code needs to look up and update that entry's referral count. Under burst traffic, this serializes writes on the most popular referrers — exactly when throughput matters most.

### 4. Webhook Reliability Under Promotion
Promoting N users fires N webhooks to potentially slow founder endpoints. Without async delivery, retry logic, and backpressure, a single slow endpoint blocks the promotion pipeline. Dead-letter handling is table stakes, not a nice-to-have.

## Product Risks

### 1. Referral Math Doesn't Actually Work
The viral coefficient math is brutal. Realistic K-factor estimates land around 0.005 — nowhere near the K>1 needed for virality. Most founders will adopt the API expecting viral growth, get supplemental growth at best, and blame the tool. The gap between the implied promise (referral-driven waitlist!) and typical outcomes (marginal lift) is the single biggest churn risk.

### 2. Inherent Disposability
Waitlists are temporary by design. Once a product launches, the API is abandoned. This caps LTV and creates structural churn. Without post-launch extensions (feature waitlists, beta cohort management, capacity throttling), the business model is a leaky bucket.

### 3. Fairness vs. Virality Is Unsolvable
Referral bumps punish early adopters who don't share. Hiding regression breeds distrust. Showing regression breeds resentment. Every design choice here alienates someone. The case studies confirm this: Clubhouse's exclusivity collapsed when opened up; Robinhood worked because the product was revolutionary, not because the queue mechanic was clever. The referral system amplifies existing demand — it can't create it, and founders with mediocre products will blame the queue design.

### 4. Fraud Surface Is Large, Detection Is Expensive
Self-referral loops, referral farms, bot signups, and incentive arbitrage are all day-one threats. But every anti-fraud measure (email verification, IP limiting, fingerprinting) adds friction that hurts legitimate users. The false positive cost is high — a legitimate viral referrer looks identical to a bot. Building fraud detection is expensive and never finished; not building it makes the referral system meaningless.

### 5. API-First May Be the Wrong Abstraction
Target users are early-stage founders, many non-technical. An API-first approach requires integration work that competes against no-code widget solutions (LaunchRock, KickoffLabs). If the API doesn't also ship an embeddable widget, it's optimizing for developer purity at the cost of addressable market.

### 6. PII Liability Concentration
The API aggregates PII across thousands of founders' user bases. A single breach exposes all of them. This makes security posture existential, not incremental — and compliance obligations (GDPR data processor, right to erasure, CAN-SPAM) add ongoing engineering cost that's easy to underestimate.

## The Meta-Risk

The biggest risk is building sophisticated referral mechanics for a problem that may not need them. The case studies show that **Hey.com succeeded with no referral mechanic at all** — the story was the viral driver. Over-investing in referral graph data structures, multi-level tracking, and scoring algorithms before validating that founders actually need more than a simple FIFO queue with email collection would be classic premature optimization at the product level.

